Abstract¶

Recent approaches to modeling stock price behavior over time have utilized machine learning techniques for increased forecasting accuracy, in comparison to traditional models. We forecast the NASDAQ-100 technology sector index, along with using Apple and Google historic stock data and Consumer Price Index data. Prior studies have shown success with using a Long-Short Term Memory (LSTM) recurrent neural network. To try to improve upon this model and to account for seasonality, we integrate an Auto Regressive Integrative Moving Average (ARIMA) model. We will evaluate the performance of this hybrid LSTM-ARIMA model compared to an ARIMA-only model.

Introduction¶

The average person’s interest in the stock market has grown immensely over the last few decades [1]. Many people, outside of Wall Street, are now trying their hand in investing in the stock market in an attempt to take advantage of this avenue of making money – and who doesn’t want to make money? If the behavior of the market can be forecasted accurately, then a more consistent profit can be made. Additionally, the technology sector is poised for growth for the rest of this decade, which makes it a prime target for stock price forecasting [2]. Stock prices in themselves are also notoriously volatile and difficult to predict - if markets are truly efficient and prices instantly reflect all public information, then a blindfolded monkey throwing darts at stock listings would probably perform as well as a professional investor. This desire for more accurate forecasting for stock price behavior motivates the use of machine learning in order to do these predictions [3].

Among the numerous methods that have been used for stock price forecasting, prominent algorithms that have been widely used in recent studies include artificial neural networks (ANN), support vector machines (SVM), and long short term memory recurrent neural networks (LSTM RNN) [4,5]. A range of different datasets have also been called upon to feed into these algorithms, including time-series data of available stock price information and macroeconomic information [3].

Data¶

The main data sets used in this project are stock data for the NDXT-100, Apple, and Google . The NDXT-100 is the abbreviation for the NASDAQ-100 technology sector, and is a stock index made up of several technological companies. Data on the Consumer Price Index (CPI) is also used.

The NDXT-100 data contains the date, index value, net change in price, and high and low prices. The Apple and Google stock datasets include the date, open price, close/last price, volume traded, high price, and low price. Both of these stock datasets are available daily on those days when the New York Stock Exchange are open. The CPI data is available monthly.

The CPI data was initially organized with the year as the row and the month as the column. This caused there to be an additional step of data processing required to reformat the data into a form that could be worked with more easily.

Methodology¶

We want to combine ARIMA and LSTM together to forecast the index value of NDXT-100 with the data detailed in the section above. LSTM excels in identifying complex patterns but may struggle with capturing overall linear trends. ARIMA provides error correction and enhances robustness against volatility and is good with linear trends. Combining both models to create a hybrid LSTM-ARIMA model allows us to hopefully improve accuracy in predicting stock market behavior by capturing both local non-linear and global linear trends. Figure 1 below outlines the structure of our methodology.

The methodology is split into three stages:

  1. Stage 1 involves fitting an ARIMA model -- outlined in the $y(t)$ equation below -- to every dataset and then taking the residual between the data and the fit. The ARIMA hyperparameters for each dataset are obtained using a stationarity test for i and the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) for p and q, with the AIC equation shown below. The residual between the data and the ARIMA fit, also shown in an equation below, is calculated for input into Stage 2.
$y(t) = \mu + \epsilon_t + \sum^{P}_{p=1}a_i y(t-p) + \sum^{Q}_{q=1}\theta_q \epsilon_{q-1} + \sum^{D}_{d} dX_{t-1} - X_{t-d}$
$AIC = -\frac{2}{N}log(L) + \frac{2}{N}k$
$residual = y_{data} - y_{ARIMA \, Fit}$

  1. Stage 2 introduces the LSTM portion of the hybrid model. By training an LSTM on the residuals from the ARIMA model, we hope it learns the unpredictable or nonlinear aspects of the data that ARIMA misses.

  2. Stage 3 combines the determined ARIMA hyperparameters and trained LSTM model to forecast into the future. Both the ARIMA model and LSTM model for the residual are forecasted into the future. Added the results of these two forecasts together results in the combined forecast from both models. For our work, we forecast 80 days into the future due to the sampling rate of our data.

Figure 2: A hand-drawn diagram roughly outlining the methodology process taken.

Finding the Residuals of the Datasets from an ARIMA Fit Using AIC Criterion¶

To demonstrate the method which was used to perform the ARIMA fitting for each time series, the process will be shown for a single time series, the high price of Apple stock.

First the stationarity of each dataset is determined. The stationarity of each time series is determined using an Augmented Dickey-Fuller test, as shown in the following block of code. This test allows us to determine whether or not each time series is stationary. This allows the hyperparameter $i$ in the ARIMA model to be determined. Stationary series are assigned a value $i=0$ and time series that are not stationary are assigned a value of $i=1$.

Here we find that the time series of the high value of Apple stock is not stationary. This means that the high value of Apple stock will be fit using an ARIMA model with the hyperparameter $i=0$.

The next step in the process of completing the ARIMA fitting is to find the values of the hyperparameters $p$ and $q$ using the AIC criterion. The best values for these hyperparameters for the High value of Apple stock is shown in the following block of code.

It should be noted that within the full code for this project the value of $p$ was allowed to vary between $0$ and $20$ and the value of $q$ was allowed to vary between $0$ and $10$. Here the possible values of $p$ and $q$ are restricted further to reduce the time required to find the best values for demonstration purposes.

In [ ]:
# @title
import warnings

def getPandQ(dataColumn):
  i = stationary
  aics = np.zeros((6,6))
  for p in range(6):
      for q in range(6):
        try:
            mod = sm.tsa.ARIMA(dataColumn, order=(p,i,q))
            mod = mod.fit()
            #print(mod)
            aics[p][q] = mod.aic

        except:
            aics[p][q] = np.nan

  p,q = np.where(aics == np.nanmin(aics))
  print(f"p: {p[0]}")
  print(f"q: {q[0]}")
  return p[0], q[0]

with warnings.catch_warnings():
  warnings.simplefilter("ignore")
  p, q = getPandQ(data['High_AAPL'])

p: 3
q: 5

Once the best hyperparameters were found using the AIC criterion, the ARIMA fit itself could be found using those hyperparameters. The fitting is completed by using the method provided in the stats models time series package in Python.

The residuals are also then obtained by subtracting the ARIMA fit from the actual data.

Both the fitting of the ARIMA model and the calculation of the residuals are shown in the following block of code.

In [ ]:
# @title
# we are evaluating the high value of apple stock
column_name = 'High_AAPL'

# create the ARIMA model with the best found hyper parameters
arima_model = sm.tsa.ARIMA(data[column_name], order=(p, stationary, q))
# fit the model to the data
model_fit = arima_model.fit()

# find the ARIMA prediction of the data
prediction = model_fit.predict(start = 1, end=len(data[column_name]))
# calculate the residual from the ARIMA fit
residual = data[column_name] - prediction

We will now plot both the ARIMA fit and the residuals to show one example of the general structure of the fits and residuals.

Using ARIMA to Generate Predictions of NDXT-100 behavior¶

The final step in our analysis utilizing ARIMA is to complete the ARIMA prediction. A prediction of the final 80 days in the dataset is completed using ARIMA on the value of the NDXT-100 as a forecast 80 days into the future is desired. The hyperparameters used for this prediction are found using the AIC criterion similarly to those shown above.

# @title
# predict the value of NDXT-100
column_name = "IndexValue_NDXT"
#predict the last 80 days of the data set (since it is sampled every four days this is 20 data points)
N_test = 20
# the best hyperparameters for the ARIMA model found using the AIC Criterion
p = 5
i = 0
q = 5

#create the ARIMA model
arma_model = sm.tsa.ARIMA(data.iloc[:-N_test][column_name], order=(p, i, q))
model_fit = arma_model.fit()

# generate the ARIMA prediction and the confidence interval
prediction = model_fit.get_forecast(N_test)
yhat = prediction.predicted_mean
yhat_conf_int = prediction.conf_int(alpha=0.05)

This forecast was also saved as a CSV file and can be accessed on Github through this link. The forecast is shown in Figure 6 below in the Results section.

Using LSTM to model the residual behavior¶

A Long Short Term Memory (LSTM) Neural Network was then used to predict the residuals of the ARIMA fit. The LSTM was trained on all of the residuals generated from ARIMA fits using the AIC criterion.

The dataset was loaded from a CSV file containing residual index values. Missing entries are removed along with an extraneous index column (Unnamed: 0). Standardization was performed before any neural network analysis; this was performed using StandardScaler from sklearn, ensuring that each feature had zero mean and unit variance.

Necessary Python libraries are imported first below.

To train the model, the scaled time series data was split into 80% training and 20% testing. This approach ensures temporal continuity, a crucial factor in time series modeling, avoiding information leakage from future data into the past.

In [ ]:

As the next step, wi'll reshaping the data into sequences of time steps, where the model learns to predict future values based on a window of past values. Each input sequence (X) consists of 100 previous time steps, and each target output (y) is the next value in the sequence. This effectively structures the input for a sequence-to-vector prediction task, where the network uses past time steps to predict the next feature vector.

In [ ]:
# @title
def create_dataset(data, look_back=100):
    X, y = [], []
    for i in range(len(data) - look_back):
        X.append(data[i:i + look_back, :])
        y.append(data[i + look_back, :])
    return np.array(X), np.array(y)

X_train, y_train = create_dataset(training_set, look_back=100)
X_test, y_test = create_dataset(test_set, look_back=100)

The LSTM model was built using the Keras Sequential API with the following architecture:

  • Input Shape: 100 time steps × 15 features
  • Layer 1: LSTM (64 units, relu, return_sequences=True) + Dropout (0.2)
  • Layer 2: LSTM (64 units, relu) + Dropout (0.2)
  • Dense Layer: 32 units, relu + Dropout (0.2)
  • Output Layer: 15 units (for predicting all features at next step)

Figure 6: Schematic of the LSTM neural network architecture. It consists of an input layer, two 64-neuron LSTM layers, a 32-neuron dense layer, and an output layer.

In [ ]:
# @title
from keras import layers
def create_lstm_model(input_shape):
    model = Sequential([
        # Input layer, shape 100 * 15
        layers.InputLayer(input_shape=input_shape),

        # LSTM layer 1
        layers.LSTM(units=64, return_sequences=True, activation='relu'),  # Increased units
        layers.Dropout(0.2),

        # LSTM layer 2
        layers.LSTM(units=64, return_sequences=False, activation='relu'), # Added another LSTM layer
        layers.Dropout(0.2),

        # Dense layer 1
        layers.Dense(units=32, activation='relu'), # Added a Dense Layer
        layers.Dropout(0.2),

        # Output layer
        layers.Dense(units=15)  # Predict the next 15 time steps
    ])
    return model
def prepare_data(data, n_steps_in, n_steps_out):
    """
    Prepares the data for the LSTM model.

    Args:
        data (np.ndarray): The time series data.
        n_steps_in (int): The number of time steps to look back.
        n_steps_out (int): The number of time steps to predict.

    Returns:
        tuple: A tuple containing X and y, the input and output sequences.
    """
    X, y = [], []
    for i in range(len(data) - n_steps_in - n_steps_out + 1):
        seq_x = data[i:i + n_steps_in]
        seq_y = data[i + n_steps_in:i + n_steps_in + n_steps_out]
        X.append(seq_x)
        y.append(seq_y)
    return np.array(X), np.array(y)
input_shape = (10, 15)
model = create_lstm_model(input_shape)

Results¶

Model Loss Behavior¶

The results of training the LSTM model with the details above is shown in Figure 7 below. The training loss shows a downward trend, indicating learning, while the validation shows an upward trend, indicating the lack of learning done by the neural network. Considering that the residual data is essentially random noise, this is not unexpected validation loss behavior.

LSTM + ARIMA and ARIMA-only Prediction and Forecast¶

Since a forecast 80 days into the future is desired, a prediction for the residual for the last 80 days in the dataset is made. The model uses the final 10 known time steps (before the withheld period) to initiate predictions.

In [ ]:
# @title
look_back = 10
scaled_data_new = scaled_data[:-20]
last_sequence = scaled_data_new[-look_back:]
input_seq = last_sequence.reshape(1, look_back, 15)

For each of the next 20 time steps (equivalent to 80 days of market data sampled every four days), the LSTM generates a prediction. The predicted value is then appended to the sequence to forecast subsequent steps.

In [ ]:
# @title
future_predictions = []

for _ in range(20):
    next_pred = model.predict(input_seq, verbose=0)[0, -1]
    future_predictions.append(next_pred)
    next_pred_reshaped = np.repeat(next_pred, 15).reshape(1, 1, 15)
    input_seq = np.concatenate((input_seq[:, 1:, :], next_pred_reshaped), axis=1)

Since the model operates on normalized data, predictions are transformed back to their original scale.

The mean-square errors for the ARIMA+LSTM hybrid model and the ARIMA only model are $2.07\cdot10^5$ and $2.03\cdot10^5$ respectively, for the 80 day prediction. Since the residual acts as random noise, it may cause the ARIMA moving average to deviate from said average more compared to the data, giving a worse MSE value. This shows that the hybrid model performs slightly worse than an ARIMA only model for this test case, and does not provide significant improvement upon the ARIMA only model shown in Figure 5.

A forecast of the moving average with ARIMA is shown in Figure 9 below. The stock price is forecasted to rise slowly 80 days into the future.

Conclusions and Future Work¶

Overall, the use of an LSTM model to predict the residuals of the ARIMA fits does not improve the prediction or forecasting of the behavior of the NDXT-100 value. The ARIMA fitting performed was able to fit the stock data very well, causing the residuals to be purely noise and not contain any sort of underlying structure. This meant that there was no structure for the LSTM to be able to learn from the data. Random noise cannot be predicted by any model, and so the use of an LSTM does not improve the accuracy of this model.

To improve the prediction and forecast, something has to change inherently about the approach to the problem. If the ARIMA residuals always look like noise, then using an LSTM neural network will not achieve anything. Though work can be done to make the ARIMA fit worse in hopes of obtaining structure in the residual data, the biggest area of change can be to include news headline data with sentiment analysis, which is one of the biggest influences on stock behavior. More varied stock data (i.e. materials index data that is used commonly in the technology sector, macroeconomic information, and incorporation of technical indicators (i.e. more quantitative analysis on historical price data before inputting data) can also be done to potentially improve on this project.
